This is one of my first games in GK

typical e4 starting
i usually use italian opening

but playing with Queen?
i wasnt expecting that
opening the way of my bishop

i think this is a bad move
throwing away your Knight outside of battle area
using Queen in early stage gives me advantage of improving my weapons
trying to force back my bishop

i reconsider this move
i think i could do a better one
this is to avoid a f4 and also targets the black knight
my opponent made a easy mistake
and lost the rook

making another mistake in hurry
i have problems about using the time
i am really lucky he chose the bishop
i have no idea why he made this move..  g6 would be better or h6
where would you move in this situation?
that is the worse choice and ends the game

i am new at chess and tring to be better
i really be grateful if you share your opinions
My favorite first move.
He responds normally.
I was trying something new so I decided to play g3 early.
He opens up his knight protecting his pawn from any threats.
I get my bishop out of the way for castling.
He opens up his other knight - what I would usually do.
I decided to try to persuade him to take my pawn then threaten his knight repeatedly but…
…He doesn't take my pawn but instead pushes up his pawn on the wing up two squares something that I think is pointless.
I threaten his pawn on e5 while being protected by my knight on f3 and my queen.
He protects his pawn using another one of his pawns.
I castle.
He pushes up his pawn same as I did on my second move.
I protect my pawn with my rook.
He opens up his bishop. I do this often.
I fork his knight and bishop with my pawn. :D
He threatens my knight but it's easier for me to take his bishop with my pawn rather then taking the knight.
I take his bishop.
He takes my knight with his own and I am now in check.
I take his knight.
And he takes my free pawn. But notice that the other pawn is right in front of him. Now both of his e can't move anywhere.
I open my knight… Finally.
He pushes up his pawn one square.
I open up my other bishop. Now both my bishops and my knight are mobile and have a fair amount of space to move around in.
Not a great move. It isn't doing anything except preventing him from castling unless he wants to open up his rook.
I pin the knight with my bishop.
He threatens me with a pawn.
And I take his knight.
He takes me back.
I threaten: Nc7.

He castles but now I see something else a possibility…
16. Na7+ Kb8 17. Nc6+! Forking the knight and rook!
I attempt my plan…
…And it works!! :D
I fork his king and rook!
He moves his king out of the way and I happily capture his rook.
Yay!
He takes my knight but now I'm plus 4 up with two rooks!
I push up my pawn.
And he pushes up his own.
I threaten his a-pawn while being protected by my c-pawn.
He ignores the threat and prepares to open up his bishop.
Now I'm really threatening his pawn.
But again he ignores it!
I take the pawn…
…And he takes mine.
…I take his…
…And he doesn't take mine!

Now I'm planning:
25. axb6 cxb6 26. Qa8+ Kd7 27. Bb5+
He pushes up his pawn again and now my plan can work.
I take his pawn…
…And he takes mine! Perfect!
The plan is working…
Yes!
Yes!!
This is good.
I check him with my queen ignoring the queen swap.
YAY!!! Checkmate in one move.

I checkmate him with my bishop my queen blocking his escape routes. :)
Believe it or not I didn't actually checkmate him here in the blitz game. I actually played: Bc4! :D But then I won his rook and he reigned. Apart from not checkmating him in the blitz game that was a great game!
My opponent opens with d4.  I myself use the queen's gambit when white so I feel that this is a strong opening move.
Play continues..
h4? white's first questionable move.  Now I'm sure theres a purpose to this but I don't see it.. maybe to defend his bishop soon to be on g5 but his bishop stays put costing white a tempo.
As I mentioned before I use the queen's gambit so I am now in a position I am very comfortable in as black.
White's knight is not threatening to me and allows me to free up my light squared bishop without losing tempo.
Now I can develop without having to worry about his pesky pawns.
It looks like he wants to break up the centre which is fine with me.
I do not feel that this is in his best interest as I am much more developed than him and if we trade off pawns I will have centre control with all my big pieces.
Capturing with my knight made it incredibly powerful. Just look at all the dark squares my centre three pieces are attacking.
Don't even ask..
A very good spot for my bishop.
Nc5??? What a blunder! Trading his only developed piece for an isolated pawn?
Just look at my development compared to white's.
Should've done that while your knight was still protecting c3.
Attacking the queen and threatening checkmate.
NOT a good time to trade queens.
Now another powerful piece joins the attack! White looks to be in trouble here.
He sees my threatened fork and moves to defend..
.. but he should have moved Rh2..
.. because this three-pronged fork and discovered attack on the rook leaves him in a much worse position than before.
Now would you take the bishop or the rook?
The bishop of course and it soon become clear why.
Ba6! Forcing the King back to e1.
.. look familiar?
With Nxg1 I would win a free bishop on f2..
.. but the result is the same.
Now it is not long before his impending doom.
Careless..
And white understandably resigns.
This is so far a fairly standard opening.
This however is not a very common move. 3. Nc3 is often played instead developing with tempo.
This would be black's standard response to 3. Nc3. Here however I think black can improve with 3. ...e5! liquidating the central pawns.

This doesn't blunder the b2 pawn. If black takes with 5. ...Qxb2?! then white can continue 6. Nc3! threatening to play Rb1 followed by Nb5 and Nxc7+ so black's best reply is 6. ...Qb6 (moving the queen yet again in the opening!) and white can rush out his pieces quickly for an attack and gain ample compensation for the pawn.

I think 6. ...c6?! left black at a disadvantage. 6. ...Qe6+!? looks like a better try as 7. Be2 is met with 7. ...Bxf3 and 7. Qe2 blocks in white's bishop slows down castling kingside and buys black time to develop with 7. ...Nc6. If 8. Qxe6 then Bxe6 is fine for black.

Once again the b2 pawn is poisoned and black should not capture it. If black does take with 10 ...Qxb2? then it is punished by 11. Nc4! Qc3 (11. ...Qb4 12. Rb1) 12. Nd6+ Ke7 (Kf8 has the same reply Kd7 is met with Ne4 followed by Ne5+ and black drops a bishop Kc8 loses to Nxf7+) 13. Ng5! Bf5 14. Ndxf7 and black quickly loses
However black resists the urge to grab material and correctly carries on developing
Preventing Nc5 and developing black's last minor piece. Black should now castle and connect the rooks.
correctly kicking away the invasive queen whilst supporting his center
trying to kick away the black bishop. black's reply is very interesting

!? I would have played either Bxf3 or Bh5. Its hard to judge if this is sound but I think this is at least playable. White should NOT continue 14. hxg4? because black replies hxg4 and the white knight can't move because of Qh2# and black would then win back his piece and have a nice attack along the h file. White should instead reply something like 14. Qd2 trying to involve his queen in the defence.
A useless gesture on the queenside that does nothing to help prevent black's attack
Its hard to assess but White's bishop vs knight advantage is probably enough to make this equal. Black's attack will be very dangerous in a few moves however so white should be quick to take action.
I don't like this move which seems to only further weaken the white kingside. Maybe white should begin attacking on the queenside?
Now white should play 18. Bg2 with a slight advantage for black. However the poisoned pawn is back although this time on g4!
Blunder. White can't resist the urge to grab material.
the correct response by black

Now it seems white is just a pawn up so what is black to do? There is a brutal move: 19. ...Qd5!! and the queen radiates power across the whole board and white can already resign! The point is that black is threatening mate on h1 and there are only 2 ways to avoid this:  20. f3 and 20. f4. The point being that both of them allow 20. ...Qxb3 and white is a piece down with an exposed kingside!

Throwing away the win. Black can still draw from here by making use of the h file and central play but black fails to find the correct plan and gradually slips into a losing position. So near yet so far!
A bad move by black. Instead 20. ...e5! looks better and allows black to get active pieces as compensation for his pawn.
Now however the knight gets attacked and white uses the gained time to exchange rooks.
Black was threatening Rxg3+
Now black is in serious trouble as without rooks there is less chances for counterplay
Now after the queen exchange the extra pawn makes itself felt
White begins by activating his king - a good start in many endgames.

black's best try is to attempt to keep the black king away from his pawns  or to try to get all the pawns on one side. white knows this and creates holes in the black position before exchanging. black is lost with correct play at this point.
Exchanging knights would only make the situation worse
white's king is temporarily forced back but black's kingside structure is now no longer flexible and is a target for the white knight
The king goes to plug the queenside hole
black has nothing better than shuffling his pieces around while white gradually improves his position
isolating the e4 pawn is a good idea as it is easier to attack
Nf6 was a more stubborn way to defend
white now rushes to attack the e4 pawn
black would like to play 54. ...Kg5 but this loses to 55. d5! and if black takes on d5 then the c pawn queens
diagonal oppostion
black can no longer hold e4
white confines the black king to the a file
black was threatening kb1
now white can't play 66. e7? as then it would be stalemate!
an excellent move giving black a move
now the queen mops up black's pawns and its game over however there was a faster win
Now 70. Qb5+ Ka1 71. Kc3 d2 Qb2# but white misses it. However it doesn't change the outcome of the game.
74. c7 was faster
Now with 2 queens its only stalemate to worry about
mate in 2
now 78. Q8e6#. white misses this too but sees a mate in 2
Well played by both sides and a very interesting game! All comments and corrections are welcome and thank you for reading :)

My opponent chose a very drawish opening variation not blaming him I use it frequently too... but he over reached and tried to push for an impossible win eventually lost his focus and and allowed me to drive the game in to a won technical endgame.
Ruy Lopez
main line d4
diverging from main lines to try avoiding drawish Rd1+ sequences h3 supports a future g4 push to improve my king side pawn majority...
now if Ne7 I have Ng5 hitting the e6 bishop known to be by far the best minor piece in this kind of structures
the idea is to exchange N by B but black still has a lot of defensive resources this is a very solid and technical variation in the Ruy Lopez...
I shouldn't bother with this it opens the h column but then what can black do with it my king and my rooks will control any infiltration squares after an hypothetical and almost certain future Kg2
... so I develop further it temporarily blocks the bishop but allows c3 at any time if needed
expected
no further delay let's exchange with a zwichenzug
and get the pawn back
the bishop is again free to move
black still has the better bishop but he still hasn't solved the problem of connecting his rooks...
and now the long planed Kg2 controls the infiltration squares for the rook on the h column
...surely to connect rooks... is my opponent reading my notes?

now I gain space the idea is to block black's queen pawns back and then try to infiltrate on the opposed wing to so some damage progressing laterally on to the other wing to profit from the space advantage (this all far in the future strategy let's see If my opponent allows this to happen)
forced but within the planed strategy
no problem there the king on g2 does miracles controlling black's rooks on the open and semi-open columns
adding a defender to the f2 pawn to free knight and rook from defending it plus I also connect my rooks with two options Rad1 or Rh1 to exchange rooks
threatening e6 and offers the exchange of bishop by knight
black decides not to exchange he will try to hold the position with the remaining pieces
headed to d4 with tempo to hit e6 on the other side
and here it is now black doesn't have Rh6 any more so the e pawn is lost unless he defends it with the king
? allows me to create a passed pawn and loses the c7 pawn for nothing as my king is controlling black's g pawn progression to promotion now I shall win this game
and black doesn't have any more checks
gains space defends e5 and block's the 4th rank to black rooks of course I expect Rgh8 at any time seeking counterplay on the h column
black seeks also some elbow space to ensure some maneuverability
occupies the open d column and prevents Kd7
here it is
and now black can trap my knight on c7 but he can't force the capture at least not without giving back some material compensation...
centralizing the king were the action is bound to happen...
black is overreaching he had better chances for a draw if he avoided exchanges... the idea must be to reach the other wing pawns for some counter-play but this disregards his own king's wing defense
I was expecting either Ra3 or Rc3 to both of which I would have replied with Bd4 to control g7 and threatening mate in h8 now I just don't see the point of 34...Rxf2 after this move by black...
Rh2 is just pointless if he want the a pawn lets see him grab it!
secures the f pawn and threatens Bd6
now I'll force some exchanges to simplify the endgame
not forced but black had nothing better
still playing out the game in disbelieve I think...

the pragmatic approach entering a technical won endgame that denies black any counter-play by exchanging his last pieces and profiting from my more advanced pawn and remaining piece to force the promotion

and now I'll bring the king to defend the e pawn and if needed next I'll block the a pawn and force black to move his c pawn releasing d5 for a check with my knight pushing e7 next followed by Nf6 to secure the promotion square but I expect my opponent to resign soon
Always.  Always 1. e4
Caro-Kann
My own personal favorite having experimented with the advance variation with the Panov-Botvinnik attack and even 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3!?
Just like the standard advance variation.
To stop e6 a pawn sacrifice that can powerfully shut down the queenside and open up the h5-e8 diagonal in many situations.  This is the most common move.

Ok.  White's idea is to keep the f-pawn open.  One idea for white that I did not follow is: 4. Nd4!? Bg6 5. f4 e6 6. g4 h7 (Be4? 7. Rg1 with d3 to come) and the question becomes whether the e6 breakthrough will be worth the trouble of the knight being kicked with a timely c5.  Alternatively trying for the pawn sacrifice with 5. e5!? is somewhat less convincing because the bishop controls the diagonal to the king and has moved out of the queenside.  Furthermore the knight on d4 hinders the often useful control of e5 for white making the counter-sac or potentially supported push e5 desirable and freeing at some point.
The only consistent response.

5. e4 puts us right back in more mainline channels.  5. e6 was possible with d4 to follow.  It seems far less convincing here because again the bishop is not hindered and covers the important kingside light-squares.
Not 5...h7?! 6. f5! Bh7 7. e6 fxe6? 8. Qh5+ (8. fxe6!?) Kd7 (8...g6 9. fxg6 Nf6? 10. g7+! winning a rook) 9. fxe6+ where black's King will find itself in a good deal of trouble.
Now white sees that it is most correct to insist on classical lines of play.
?  Black has already taken precautions to safeguard his bishop (5...e6).  This loses crucial time.  Instead 6...Nd7 or 6...c5 look to be dynamically equal for black.

White is happy to trade off black's "bad" bishop for his good one as this will win him time.  The DSB is outside the pawn chain anyway and has moved twice already not counting the h6 move that made more space for him.  Thematic and good.

? A very bad move.  Black's idea was to get this bishop out with time possibly finding some squares of activity on the queenside before c3 removes all of its options except e7.  However this move can still be answered by...
Obvious and good.  This move stops black from winning time and asks it where it's going.

?! Stubbornly consistent and bad.  We shall see that black's bishop was sorely missed from the kingside.  Relatively best was 9...Be7 but white's space and time advantages should give him a good edge.
It's certainly possible for white to keep his options open with a move like 10. Be3 preparing a queenside castle.  Nevertheless this move aims to quickly punish black for his sloth in the opening.

?  More mistakes.  I think black was forced to play 10...g6 here with an obviously grim defensive task in store.  White should probably just mobilize his forces with Be3 and Nd2 after g6 hoping to exploit the weak dark squares later.
White ahead in king safety space and development looks to bust things open.  Obvious and good.

?! The f-file is coming open no matter what but maybe this was black's last chance to castle.  White should then refrain from fxe6 and instead develop his back rank.  Here white just has too much play and the black king too few defenders.

?  Black is probably losing on any move but this is convincingly crushed immediately.  On 12...Nxf5 13. Nxf5 0-0 white has the strong rook lift with Rf3 or Qh5 and Bxh6 in store.  If white stays in the center with his king say 13...Qe7 White can just marshall his pieces for a timely e6.  Even Re1 immediately (not waiting to slide the a-rook over) looks strong.
Owch.
Well what else was there to try? 13...Nxf5 14. Rxf5 gxh6? 15. Qg3+ Followed by Rf6 and (if necessary) Qh4.  And if not gxh6 white has comfortably won a pawn that defends black's exposed king.
14...Kg7 is harder to crack but with the black king so exposed white has all the time in the world and may even just consider Nf5+ followed by Rf3 (Nxf5? Rxf5!).
Also convincing is Nf7+ not only winning the exchange but also bringing White's rook to the powerful seventh rank.
What else can black try?  This at least hopes to interpose Qh4.

Highlighting black's helplessness.  Nxf7++ also wins; the queen cannot interpose as the knight is also checking.  The text stops black from entertaining any hopes of f6 and also blocks the black queen's defense.
On any queen move (to avoid the fork) black falls on his sword by Nxf7++ and Qh8(6) mate.
Ruthless.
Black is helpless. 1-0.
My favourite.
I know this is called "a loss of tempo". Probably it is as this game shows. But it is the base for an early g4-g5 that makes always shake black's kingside if he is not familiar with the position.

This is an early choice for black. Normally players go Be7 etc. This challenges me at once: either I let him exchange the bishops (and I reckon it is played and not regarded as "bad" for white but it is not my choice) or I go for e5.

Now white's play is to keep the tension and develop quicly while black deals with this knight. It means f6. For this black has to move his knight and can put it on e4. Normally this is not a problem for white (even if it is a specular outpost) but in this very situation it becomes so.

This is to support quickly Ne5 with the other knight. Black can go c5 and then Qc7 and attack. I must be prepared this was the knight's move purpose. And it's thematic. White plans to close the queenside with c3. 
But maybe an improvement should be made on this line.
First this one thematic too that opens the lsb's way but much more important prevents the knight to jump to h5 after a future g5. Of course it doesn't solve the e4 placement.

If I prepare this move with f3 in order to prevent the knight's jump to e4 after g5 I self-block my queen's action on h5 that turns to be a nice outpost for the black's knight. I don't want him to exchange my bishop so I have to retire it to h2 and this gives black a valuable tempo for further defence. 
So I go for it at once maybe underestimating the power of his knight in e4.
Ok also thematic. Black can choose to close my lsb with c5 or this exchange. Both are good IMO.
Here he goes with the attack on the knight. Ok. I'm prepared.

Now my g5 plan doesn't work anymore. Ok I just have to prepare it. 
By the way: would Qe2 have been better? I see a very interesting line over there: after 10. Qd2 Qxc2. In my view white can go 11. NxN (tactic because it leaves the bishop en prise). Best black's seems to be BxBf4 leaving white with the exchange 12. NxRf8 KxN. After it white frees the docks with Nf3. 
But wait: what if black goes after the a1 rook with: 12. NxRf8 Qxb2! ? White goes 13. Nb3 it seems the most sensible move. Black may want to exchange queens then taking the Nf8 and the game proceeds quietey or go for 13.... Qc3+ 14. Kd1 Ne5 after which white is very unconfortable. Not whorty to try to grab a pawn (Nxe6) that frees black. 
So Qe2 seems a bad choice but a lot must be said for sure.
Here he goes. I know his next one will be f6. The NxN "threat" is a good way to get out of the situation... or it is not???

Another move more in the spirit of white's way of play was 11. g5. The idea is that after 11.... f6 12. gxf6 Nxf6 13. Rg1 attacking. Or 12... Rxf6 that leads to strange lines like this one: 13. NxN and if RxB 14. Ne5 BxNe5 15. dxe5 and I'm too tired to find out more. It is an interesting position.

fen="r1b3k1/ppq3pp/4p3/3pP3/4nr2/5N1P/PPP2P2/R2QKB1R b KQ -"

I think white loses after Qa5+ followed with the knight sac with either c3 Ke2 or Nd2. Do you agree? The three are interesting believe me :-)
Now as white I cannot say I have a good position after the exchanges... so Bd3 was not good either. But let's go on with the exchanges.
Ok a quieter situation. What is left for white? Nothing. I have to rebuild an attack.

This knight is not an inmediate threat and surely it doesn't deserve b3. 
But I overlooked...
...disregarding the threat in h7. Sometimes these checks are a self trap so be careful.
I think I can hold.
Back doesn't have too much yet... right?
...so I go for a try. Let's see if I can make something of this after all.
Not exactly a bunder since Kh8 lead to a well-known Ng6+ KxN NxR++ and white seems to win the attack - if not the game.
But this allows my queen in and now black is suddenly shaked! :-)
My problem is that Nf5+ obvuious like it seems is not the proper move to win.
So I tried this one instead. R h8 is impossible.
Crazy as it seems I had the plan to win by bringing a rook into the fray and not anyhow else. So I allowed "some" pawn's munch.
I thought about queenside but then the hungry pawn would have eaten with check and I didn't had time enough to calculate but it looked very dark.
Yes opening the way for the lsb's action... scary. As it will prove to be.
Rook into the fray. Ok.
!!! I didn't see it. Ok so let's be aggressive (the wise bxc3 is out from my repertoire on a blitz wild game... that's because I lose so much).
As if I had calculated it :-)
Easy to see isn't it?
If Kg2 d4 is lethal. Maybe Kf1?
The only defence and I thought that it will hold. I still have threats after Rg1. But black has a nasty pawn on c3 that worries me a lot.
Now Rg1 makes me very vulnerable to the pawn's advance... I had urgently to find a way to get out of this. So I HAD to bet for my only chance...
It turned out to be good. But who would have said that?
Believe it or not I'm looking for a PERPETUAL here.
I can defend from mate with Rg1 (the ONLY one move: white's queen cannot reach a square to defend g2) but then I'll be probably crushed by black pawns.
So this is a nice turn. I can save myself with gxR. It defends my g2 but then black can go Qxb2 and... I was running out of time too!
This was even more adventorous. I can win a lot with my queen's chechs but it is not possible while black grabs g2.
I have to be sure that I will have checks all the time.
Incredibly enough I think I have perpetual. Then... Could I win?
I already decided to try a plan so I want to put my queen on the right spot.
He is struggling to avoid perpetual and he must have been very surprised when I broke the checks! The fact is I think I would have perpetual or I'll deal with the black pawns.
I expected something like Qxb2 but black is decided to win and finds another very good mate threat: Qg3 Qxh3. I AM AGAIN AT THE SAME POINT than before. My queen cannot get on time to defend g3 OR h3!
What else? Going for the perpetual again!
...and THIS gave me a chance. The perpetual trap is really so strong for black as his grimp on g2/g3 is for me. Isn't it interesting?
Getting the other rook into the fray and allowing a DOUBLE mate threa on my king. Now this move is "unnatural".
So stupidly here I didn't consider Qb5+ followed by RxB. But be aware: the pawns are still there. So I opted for...
More tactics. If Qe6+ Kmoves and then Qe3+ forcing the queen's exchange but again his pawns are there - well one of them. But wait.

I cannot take the rook so lightly. Black threats f3 and I have to go for a perpetual again. Noooo! :-). But Qxb2 will be enough to win since I cannot stop the pawns. So I CAN'T TAKE that juicy rook! What a nightmare!
Those pawns must be dealt with.
Probably a blunder. But it is true that I still CANNOT take the rook and - oh no not again! - needing a perpetual to survive!
WAIT! Black probably desperate thinks that with a rook against a knight he could win. And propose a liberatory queen's exchange. Was it good?

Now cxd4 was ok? After losing the knight for a pawn I have two joined pawns on g an h... after the impressive pawn's center black has now to fear MY pawns... BUT black has a tiny little pawn on a7... and for this "insignificant" pawn I gave up the idea.
I know I will have to sac the knight but let's see.

Not the best choice of course. I think that dxc3 would have been crushing me. 

Let's see this: 55. cxd4 fxN 56. Kxg2 Kxa2 57. h4 a5 58. g5 a4 

fen="r7/8/8/6P1/p2P3P/8/k5K1/8 w - -"

59. d4!

And I think black has difficulties to cope with all the pawns. Say: 

59.... Rd8 60 g6 Rd7 61. h5 Kb2 62. h6 A3 63. h7 

fen="8/3r3P/6P1/3P4/8/p7/1k4K1/8 b - -"

black can Rd8 g7 a2 and the situation is similar to actual game. 

if 63. ...a2 64. h8=Q+ Kb1 and now is black that has to escape perpetual. Because if g7 black gets a queen on his own and white has only checks to save him... for the third time! :-O
 



But HE was running out of tempo now...
Nice try boy but you wont' have enough for this.
Now that the situation is stalled MY pawns will win.
You'll see an amazing knight here.

AND THE ROOK CANNOT STOP the pawn!!!!!!!!!!!!! Black played excellently and the game was one of the craziest I've ever played with som many double-edged positions. 
Being fair I should have lost it I deserved it. But most important: it was FUN :-D
The King's Pawn Play.
The King's Pawn Opening.
This is the King's Knight opening and it is a transposition of the King's Pawn Play.  In addition he wants to capture black's e5 pawn for free.
Black responds by bringing out his or her queen's knight to protect the e5 pawn.
This is the Ruy Lopez opening and it is a transposition of the King's Knight opening.
In this position black and white have both developed their minor pieces.
He made this move to bring out his other knight and transpose the Ruy Lopez opening into the Double Knights Opening.

Black chose this candidate to force an exchange with Nxd4 followed by Bxd4.  By the way this was ! and the best way to handle the Double Knights Defense.  That is what I learned in a different annotation.
Because his c4 bishop is out he chose this candidate because he wants to mate black in one move with Qxf7# and that is what will happen.  I will explain this shortly.

In my opinion black chose this candidate because he or she had a Fight or Flight response and was worried that white would play b4.  Therefore he or she probably felt that there was no way out of trouble.  However this was ?? and the loosing blunder.  In fact "That looses immediately" as Jack Stockel would say.  Nf6 or f6 might have enabled him to play b4 but it would have been a better choice as it would have prevented a check mate.  That is because he now has an inevitable mating pattern against black and will mate him or her in one move with Qxf7#.

There is an important lesson to learn from this game.  There is usually a way out of trouble and this is feasible 99.7% of the time according to Jack Stockel.  On the other hand I used to think that there was only one way out of a bad situation and that put me through a "Fight of Flight" response. In addition it caused me to be pessimistic and inflexible so I used to make moves that I felt were forced.  However those moves were also loosing blunders in some cases.  Now I remember that there is generally more then one way out of trouble. That is because I remember Jack Stockel's advice to "Think about things" and "there is always another way to do something"... as chesskingdom64 would say.  However there are then better ways to address a problem. The question then becomes the best way.  That is because there is one way that works the best but there are other solutions as well.  After all "The glass is half full not half empty" as they say.  Therefore I now try to solve a problem.  Then I try to find a better solution to the problem.  This method is helping me to become a better chess player.  When a problem occurs (due to a blunder or an unexpected position) I view it as an extremely difficult equation with many solutions.  Then I solve the problem by narrowing it down until I find the best solution.

White has three pawns in the middle of the board in attacking position while Black is in a more reserved position with his bishop weaker than White's engaged knight.

White could do some more positioning but would rather attack the middle of the board before it gets clogged with Black's pieces.

White's knight was moved to try and combat a fork he foresaw from the knight and is now attacking the knight while Black is trying to move his second knight.

In the Sicilian defense per Kasparov one of the biggest challenges for white is to deal with the two center pawns for black.  White's challenge is to neutralize those pawns and black's challenge is to not trade them away cheaply.
Fairly standard progression so far.  Nothing out of the ordinary.

This move has good instinct in that it is designed to stake a claim to the center and force me to move my knight.  Any piece that has reach into your side of the board should be viewed with extreme caution.  If you allow pieces to stick around they can have long-term consequences to your game play.
Instead of retreating I decide to invade a little deeper into Black's territory.  A pair of mutually protected knights is a good thing.

A wrong move here can spell some problems for my side if I'm not careful.  If I choose not to take the d5 pawn then he can advance the pawn one space and force me to move my knight around while staking a strong claim to the center.  However I have three options at this point.  I can take with the knight take with the pawn or move my bishop to g5 to pin his knight against his queen allowing me to move my knight to the d5 square (provided he doesn't pin my own knight with a reciprocal Bb4).  To avoid all of those pin issue I prefer to take with the e pawn.

If black had decided to immediately retake with his f6 knight instead I would have won a knight in the process.  This is an interesting response and I think is worthy of discussion.  As this now stand black has three attackers and I have 2 defenders.  I could potentially move my bishop to c4 to protect but I see problems down that road.  With proper analysis though black is potentially in trouble if I give a little nudge.

Now black has some poor options and ultimately he moves the b knight to retake the d pawn.  If black had instead decided to move to a6 I would have gotten a decent amount of advantage in development and could have added more pressure to his exposed king BUT it would have been better than this move which I will categorize as a mistake.

12.	fxe5	Qxe5
13.	Bf4	Qxe2+
14.	Bxe2	O-O
15.	Bxa6	bxa6
16.	O-O

Black appears to have an advantage here and can regain his knight however my b5 knight has a nasty surprise waiting.
I believe that this move is not necessarily one that you would naturally see.  Taking with a queen and leaving it hanging begs it to be taken.

However the follow through to allow a queen/king split is damning.  Not only has black lost the ability to castle with a very exposed king but now he is down a knight as well.  Not a good place to be if you're black.

Perhaps it might have been better to move the bishop to e6 and force me to move my knight?  Moving the bishop to f5 invites me to move my knight to the e3 square protecting the c2 pawn and attacking the bishop.

Again I think that e6 would have been a better spot for the bishop then black could ahve moved Rc1 to put some pressure on my queenside.  The other downside at this point is that I can potentially pin his bishop against his king.

Often times players are keen to grab advantages where they can and will immediately retake or take the prize.  Bringing additional pieces into the fray is often of greater strategic value and should not be neglected.  Do not throw away the chance to grab a piece or retake just to gain position but do not immediately retake or take because you can.  Analyze the board and see where you can smartly develop an attack.

This is a game I played against Shredder a few weeks ago.  Although White didn't play very well and dropped his queen to a fairly obvious tactic one of the nice things about the game is that it shows the danger of not developing your pieces and of launching unsupported attacks.  White was able to pull off the victory because Black ended up with all his pieces sidelined either having not moved or having moved away from the scene of the fight.

The Sicilian Defence.  The most popular choice for Black against 1. e4 and something that offers good chances for Black especially against weaker players who don't know quite what to do.  I didn't used to like playing against it but I'm improving.
A general developing move that doesn't commit White to anything in particular yet.

Shredder (and thus the game title) lists this as the Rossolimo Variation with White taking an almost Ruy Lopez-inspired approach.  However we should note that the Rossolimo proper has Bb5 as White's third move and Black replying with 3. ... g6 (neither of which are the case here).  We can probably consider this a transposed move order for White and a deviation from book for Black's next move.
Combines general development with an attack on the e4 pawn (which will need further support before it can come to anything).
As Black has not pursued his attack on e4 White is free to try an attack of his own at d5.
Of course Black cannot reply 7. ... Nxd4 because that would put the king in check from the bishop.
Exchanging the knights would allow exd5 with an attack on the knight.  White could also have castled for stronger defence or perhaps played Qe2.
Supporting the threatened bishop but also cutting off its lines of retreat. An exchange is the best White can expect if Black tries to pursue it.
Black opts for an immediate exchange of the bishops.

White is happy with this knight placement with one eye on a hopeful Nc7 if the queen moves before castling.  Black could play a6 to drive the knight back but it wouldn't help his position much otherwise and he might instead consider e5 (especially as White's lack of an lsb offsets the weakeness in his castle created by exchanging pawns on e6.  Black could also try Nxc4 as the pawn is no longer defended.
Instead Black develops the queen with check.  Without the c4 pawn this would have been an excellent attack and could have been usefully preceded by Nxc4.
White still eyes c7 using the discovered check to pick up the rook.
Black applies a check of his own.
?? Ke2 was probably best although Black can still play Nxb2 to some effect.
White chooses to allow his rooks to connect and to move his king away from the fight on the queenside.
White now needs good activity if he is to compensate for the loss of material.  It's fair to say that this should be over if Black gets his pieces together.
Attempting to activate the centre and the dsb.  g6 might have been better.
Attacks the knight and allows the rooks to be doubled.  Note that White passes on 17. dxe5 e.p. because the d5 pawn is blocking the d6 pawn which is itself blocking the black dsb.
The only available retreat.
Pinning the knight although it is well defended and cannot yet be taken.

White could have defended both the a2 pawn and the b4 rook by playing a3.  However this would have resulted in a cramped inflexible defence that would probably have given Black a lot of time to get more active and would have been vulnerable to a6 in particular.  White will lose a little more material but one pawn is hardly likely to make a difference now - it's activity White needs not minor material.
Qxb2 Rxb2 now would be favourable for White.

Black has his eye on the kingside pawns but the cost is a temporarily useless queen who can't do anything else from the back rank.  We should note that Black has greatly limited activity - three of his pieces haven't moved one is in imminent danger and one the queen is a little out of the action.
After a lot of time eyeing that square White finally moves to pick up the rook and is close to crippling Black's queenside.

? Black has now moved to pick up the h-pawn but is in trouble since his queenside is both a near-wasteland and is under heavy attack.  Be7 is better - it picks up the knight and gets the h-rook out and fighting.
White removes Black's last defender on the queenside.
Black's best choice - Be7 gets him mated and nothing else recovers the material.
Black can escape this fight alive thanks to the time bought by White needing to capture the a7 pawn but will need to be a little careful.

Black's other options:
A: 24. ... Kc8 25. Rb8+ Kd7 26. R2b7+ Kd6 Rd8#
B: 24. ... Kd8 25. Rb8+ Ke7 and Black escapes the mate threat.
C: 24. ... Ke8 25. Nc7+ and Black again escapes.

Kd6 still allows Black to get out if he plays the right move (e4).
White now threatens mate in one to which Black must respond.

But he does not.  It's odd that the computer overlooks a mate in one but syptomatic of its problems in the game overall - not enough activity and development.  Of course it's also a result of the low difficulty setting.

Hi everyone!

My brave opponent decided to try out the Allgaier Gambit against me.  This involved sacrificing a piece to get Henry out into the open and then get at him.  Unfortunately for him Henry was able to run for cover and I was able to run away with my extra piece in the endgame.  My opponent thought this was too much and decided to wave the white flag.  So how did this happen?  Firstly I will provide the link that Gameknot Analysis has given to help you through this game.  http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=17272114&fb=1&rnd=0.2644588537214342.  We start with a double KP opening 1.e4 and I respond with e5 and he gives me the KG with 2.f4 of which I accept.
2. f4 - King's Gambit.
2. ..... exf4 - I accept.
3. Nf3 - development and stops Glenda from going to h4.
5. Ng5!? - interesting move - this move allows the knight to be trapped but this also turns the KGA into the Allgaier Gambit of which I must accept because as you will see .....
6. Nxf7 - ..... Glenda and my KR are forked so in order too avoid losing a rook Henry must take the knight and face the big wide world.
7. ..... Nc6 - with Henry exposed I must get my pieces out asap.
8. ..... d5 - I must return a pawn or two in order to get my pieces out and to give Henry some cover - he's shivering poor old guy and is in dire need of some really thick medieval stockings!

9. .... Kg7 - Henry does find a modicum of refuge but with the advanced kingside pawns the cover is very flimsy indeed!  I think he needs an extra cloak as well as those stockings so Glenda must still get those knitting needles going!
10. d4 - trying to establish a formidable pawn centre.
13. ...... bxc6 - both of us trade bishops and end up with identical pawn structures on the queenside.

14. .... Qg5 - aha by express delivery we get those medieval stockings and that cloak for out comes Glenda to g4 on her broomstick to deliver them.  Should white castle kingside Glenda also eagerly awaits the WK.
15. .... Ne7 - I cannot save the f4 pawn so I decided to clear the back decks by bringing out my knight to help cover Henry and to also lend a hand to attack the WK.
17. ..... Qf5 - Glenda still hovers over the WK.
17. 0-0 - So white castles kingside.  Glenda now evades the threat of a discovered attack (Bxh6+) by swiping the undefended white pawn on h5.
18. ..... Be6 - now Fou Leblanc finally emerges and clears the decks.  Once my KR gets east of the g column I will have castled by hand.  Fou Leblanc also supports a possible knight move to d5 or f5.
19. .... Nf5 - my knight chooses f5 as it bears down onto g3.  If it were not for white's dsb then the Wicked Witch of the West and the white KR would be forked.
20. ..... Qh3 - Glenda moves very close to the WK and I now threaten to win the g3 pawn.
22. ...... Qxg3+ - and I duly win that pawn and am now a full piece up.
23. ..... Qh3+ - no I am not planning a perpetual check.  This queen check is to clear the path for g3 putting even more pressure on the WK.

24. .... g3 - I duly play this move.  Amazingly Gameknot Analysis flagged this as a mistake.  The move did prove good enough however to force resignation.  I will be interested to hear your views on the Allgaier Gambit.  Anyhow I hope you have had a good read.  Bye for now - Joanne

My opponent (a much lower-graded player whom I hoped to beat easily considering the ECF grades given above) opens with the queen pawn. Grabbing a stake in the centre and opening up lines to develop the dark-squared bishop and later queen. Standard and theoretical stuff.

A very common reply. Black also grabs his share of the centre and makes it less attractive for White to play an immediate e2-e4 (which he would like to attempt at some point to take more control of the centre).

One of the most common openings in existence: the Queen's Gambit. White apparently sacrifices a pawn (in reality most experts do not consider this a pawn sacrifice because the pawn can easily be regained and theory offers no tried-and-tested way for Black to keep hold of the extra pawn). White's purpose in playing this move is to challenge Black's stake in the centre and build pressure against the d5-pawn.

The reply which I always play against the Queen's Gambit - known simply as the Queen's Gambit Declined. A simple (yet highly theoretical) move aimed at keeping a pawn in the centre (e.g. after the unusual but playable 3.cxd5 exd5). The obvious drawback being that Black's light-squared bishop is blocked in.

The usual move in the Queen's Gambit Declined: White develops a piece and increases the pressure against Black's pawn on d5. I have played this position many times from both sides of the board. An interesting alternative is 3.Nf3.

This opening for Black is called the Tarrasch. Black opts to occupy the centre with an unstable pawn structure in exchange for long-term fast development and good spatial control. Note that it is not possible for White to win a pawn immediately although it may initially appear so: in fact 4.cxd5 exd5 5.dxc5? is a well-known equalising line for Black after 5...d4! 6.Ne4 Bxc5! 7.Nxc5 Qa5+ with the fork regaining the minor piece.
? Clearly my opponent did not know how to meet the Tarrasch - this move is an opening error! This move simply loses a pawn for White as the following moves demonstrate:

? I think that this was a mistake on my part - and the computer (Fritz 10) corroborates this judgement. I played this move in the hope that White would allow a queen exchange which would help to consolidate Black's material advantage. However 5...cxd4 is better since it affords Black a space advantage and a firm grip on the centre as well as his material advantage. Black could then have followed up with ...Nc6 and ...e5 with a powerful grip on the central dark squares.
! Avoiding a queen exchange and placing the queen on a (slightly) more useful square.

Developing a piece and aimed at exchanging off White's strong central knight thus robbing White of a useful piece. Piece exchanges I decided would be useful in consolidating my small but significant material advantage. In fact this formed my strategy for the next few moves - so much so that I unfortunately sank into positional apathy and handed over the initiative to my opponent.
Developing a piece and preparing to replace the central knight with a well-placed central bishop if the former is exchanged off.
Carrying out my strategy of exchanging pieces whenever possible.

Despite being a pawn down White now has an excellent position - his light-squared bishop holds Black's queenside in a bind as well as putting pressure on Black's kingside. I therefore decided to force this bishop to move away as follows:
?! An odd-looking move leaving Black's e-pawn backward and weak. However I was determined to dislodge White's light-squared bishop from its excellent post in the centre!

The most useful square for White to place his bishop retaining the unpleasant bind on Black's queenside. Black cannot play ...Bd7 because the b-pawn and then rook are hanging; Black also cannot play ...b6 because the pawn is pinned to the rook.
Developing a piece to a good square and preparing to castle.
Developing a piece and forcing Black's queen to give up the useful post in the centre.

By now Fritz 10 rates the position as approximately equal. If we take into consideration the fact that White is a pawn down this means that the computer believes that White has enough compensation for the pawn. I agree with the computer - White's pieces are mostly developed to excellent logical squares (whereas Black's queenside is in a bind and undeveloped and Black's central pawns are weak).
Struggling to catch up with White in the development race. I was unwilling to play 11...Nc6 because of 12.Bxc6 bxc6 giving Black horrible doubled and isolated c-pawns to worry about.
Developing the rook to an excellent square from where it controls the open d-file. White also gains a tempo in playing this move since Black must do something about his undefended bishop on d6.
Preparing to expand on the queenside with b2-b4 after which White will enjoy a queenside space advantage and the power of his queenside rook will be increased.

My strategy was still to exchange as many pieces as possible! I felt that removing White's light-squared bishop from the board would be an achievement since this would allow Black to develop his queenside via ...Bd7 or ...b6 and ...Bb7.

Black's position seems to make more logical sense than it did a few moves ago with fewer undeveloped pieces hanging around. Also Black retains his extra pawn! However I still think White enjoys the better position and White's next move grabs the initiative:
Trying to retake the initiative with threats against the pawns on h2 and c4.
Neatly parrying both threats and making Black's dark-squared bishop less useful.

The most striking difference between these two positions is the activity of the rooks and minor pieces. White's rooks and knight are all dominating the board controlling a multitude of squares; by contrast Black's rooks and bishop are all huddled on the back rank controlling hardly any squares at all! I resolved to do something to sort this out immediately:
Trying to wriggle out of the bind which White's queen imposes on Black's queenside.
Taking advantage of Black's loss of time and increasing White's space advantage on the queenside.
Pinning the c-pawn and thus preventing c5-c6 which could otherwise be an extremely annoying move for Black to face.
The bishop is starting to become more useful! Additionally this move clamps down on the c6-square preventing White's pawn from advancing any further.
White changes his plans - now he tries to put pressure on Black's backward weak e-pawn and tie down Black's bishop and queen to defending it.

Moving the bishop away from defending the weak e-pawn but White cannot take advantage of this yet because his queen is under attack. Furthermore this moves Black's bishop to a very useful diagonal - pointing directly at White's kingside where it will play a very important role later on.
I'm not sure exactly what I was trying to achieve with this move other than simply defending the e-pawn.

??! I didn't really want to play 24...Rff8 returning the rook and allowing a repetition of moves. Therefore I impulsively (and stupidly?) allowed this exchange sacrifice (sacrifice of a rook for minor piece).

A fork allowing White to pick up a pawn. However I think that this is a mistake since it leaves White's queen completely out of the game. Over the next few moves Black is able to create all the activity and set tactical problems for White largely because White's queen has become an irrelevance.
Black now has a material disadvantage so he is obliged to create activity in order to gain compensation. I achieved this by creating a series of threats as follows:
Firstly a simple threat against White's kingside - namely targeting the g-pawn.
Parrying the threat but weakening all the light squares on White's kingside.
! Aimed at exploiting the weak light squares on White's kingside. The threat is ...Qd5 followed by ...Qg2# or ...Qh1#. My opponent sank into thought at this point.
If 29...Qd5 30.f3 seems to hold White's position together. Instead I tried to create trouble by attacking White's rooks.
If 30.Rcc1 30...Qd5! reintroduces Black's threats against White's kingside light squares.
! Preparing to break open White's kingside.
Not really a rook sacrifice since 33.fxg3?? Qg2#. White's kingside is broken open and I felt sure that checkmate should follow.
The only move: if 33.Kh2 Qxf2#.
? At this point I missed a forced checkmate! 33...Qd3+! and checkmate follows in all lines e.g. 34.R5e2 Rg1+!! 35.Kxg1 Qg6+

Observe the fact that Black's pieces for the first time are all playing active roles in the game - they are all playing a part in Black's overwhelming attack! By contrast White's queen is doing absolutely nothing on a7 and White's rooks aren't particularly useful either.

I calculated that this led to a forced win as the text shows by exchanging off most of the pieces on the board into a winning rook-and-pawn endgame. Shame I didn't find the forced checkmate to crown my rather nice attack but such is life...an important skill in chess as well as in life is to know when to stop attacking exchange off all the pieces and convert the small advantage that you have gained in the attack.
! Forcing the exchange of all the pieces except one pair of rooks.

The rest is easy: Black walks his king over to d7 picks up White's last remaining pawn and promotes one of his three pawns in an easily winning endgame.

Hope you enjoyed the annotation! Comments would be welcomed! :)

This is a game I played shortly after starting to read through Vladimir Vukovic's "The Art of the Attack in Chess"; specifically the section on the attack on the king stuck in the centre.   The ideas in the book helped me to a quick win in this game.
d4 is the most common here.   I find 2. Nf3 usually indicates a weaker player unfamiliar with the French.   It's also a sign that the French exchange is on the way.
And as expected the dreaded exchange variation.
I don't think this is the strongest; it blocks the c-pawn advance.   The main line is Bd3.
Bg5 puts more pressure on black's position - trying to undermine the d-pawn and restrict black's pieces that little bit more by virtue of the x-ray onto black's queen.

7. Nb5 is a threat easily dealt with - ... Bb4+   8. c3 Ba5 and c7 is covered while white falls behind in development; a subsequent a6 will kick the knight to an awkward square.   If instead 8. Bd2 to block the check a lot of white's pressure is gone.
I think this is unnecessary for white; he may be better advised to castle now and challenge the bishop on his next move.   This may be with the bias of hindsight though!

If 9. ... Nd7 10. Qb5 looks strong for white as the b and d pawns are hanging.   Though black may be ok after 10. ... Nb6 in which case this move may just be too slow.   The d-pawn is stronger than usual because white isn't threatening to remove the knight at f6 (as he would have been with the bishop on g5)
? This is an error from white who won't get another chance at castling.   My task now is to try take advantage of the uncastled king while I can.
Swapping off often doesn't favour the attacking player but here I need to clear lines to the king.
If instead 14. PxN d4 followed by Bb4+ should cause white some problems.
The e-file has been successfully opened.

?!   Not the right plan computer analysis reckons.   Instead Re4 means the rook heads the battery not the more valuable queen.   A triple attack down the e-file is also formed quicker - Qe7 and Re8 are following; in the game my rook had to go via d6 and e6 wasting an extra move.
Preventing Kd2 while also freeing d6 for the a-rook to join the battle.

? Qf3 was better here; if I can get Re3 in white's queen will be cut off from the defence of the knight.   The computer gives as the best line 21. Qf3 Re6   22. Rae1 Re3   23. Qf2 Qe4   24. Qf1 Kf8   25. h3 (don't really understand those last three moves) RxP!   26. NxR Qxd4+   27. Kc1 BxP+   28. Kb1 BxN when black has three pawns for the exchange and a reasonably active position.
??   White needs to make room for his queen.   Better would be 22. Kd1 when after 22. ... Re3   23. Qd2 Qh3 black is going to start winning material while white is still trying to extract his pieces.

White's queen must leave the a6-c1 diagonal and as a result the knight at a minimum will fall (computer analysis recommends 23. g4).   White resigned here.   A salutary lesson to take care of your king!
